experience:
My own background is in communications and brand strategy. I was Head of Communications at Masternaut, one of the UK’s fastest growing technology businesses, which featured in The Sunday Times Tech Track 100 in 2007, 2008 and 2009, I worked closely with the founder of the business to help forge a unique brand identity and proposition, helping to create a brand that was distinct and elevated from its many commoditised competitors. We created incredibly successful PR and advertising campaigns, building awareness and advocacy for our unique business.

I believe in creating BRANDS - not BLANDS. Brands are enduring, are valuable and create lifelong fans and loyalty. Blands on the other hand wither away and die. You must make a choice! Are you going to be a BRAND or a BLAND?

In 2010 I founded The Art of Brand Storytelling, a strategic brand consultancy to help businesses of all shapes and sizes amplify the powerful stories at their heart. As well as providing strategic brand and marketing advice, I regularly speak at business conferences all over the UK - sharing my experiences and ‘brand manifesto’ first hand.
qualifications: Bsc (Hons) Management with a specialism in Marketing - Manchester Business School
biography:
Hi I’m Alex. You may remember me as one of Lord Sugar’s candidates in series 6 of The Apprentice. I’ve joined Pimp My Cause as I think it has the power and potential to make a huge difference to charities and organisations not just in the UK, but all over the world. It’s about crowdsourcing the expertise of talented marketers who are hungry to get involved in making a difference in society.

As a Brand, Marketing and PR specialist, I’ve realised that the most successful organisations are often those that can shout the loudest - and that means spending lots of money on big budget campaigns. Not everyone has such deep pockets. There are causes out there with amazing stories waiting to be told - they just need a helping-hand to make themselves heard. By ‘adopting’ a good cause, talented people can help make a big difference, sharing powerful ideas, expertise and creative thought. Pimp My Cause is a new era for charitable organisations - and I’m a staunch supporter!

I look forward to helping to spread the Pimp My Cause movement - helping many good causes along the way.

Let your own Pimp My Cause story begin.... Get involved!

biography:
Are you looking to raise more funding by using measurable marketing activity? Are you open to testing new ideas, keeping the ones that work and ditching the ones that don't work? Are you looking for a fresh insight from someone with experience of what works in marketing?

If the answer to any of the above is yes, please read on and I'll explain how I can help you achieve all of the above.

I've always specialised in measurable marketing activity. My background was initially in direct marketing - direct mail, telesales, door drops and a wide range of other media. I've worked in financial services, utilities and telecoms, and in all of these sectors there is a real focus on the numbers, so I've had to adapt, learn and test new ideas over the years to find out what works and what doesn't.

From there, not surprisingly I've also built up a specialism for internet marketing, which is even more measurable still. I've built websites, helped clients get their sites found on Google, managed pay per click advertising campaigns and helped them make sense of their web analytics data.

If you're looking for support at a more strategic level, I can help with that too. I'm a tutor for the Chartered Institute of Marketing diploma programme and I regularly have to help students from a wide variety of industry sectors to put together their strategic marketing plans for their assignments.

If you'd like to know more, contact me. I'll be happy to give you a few pointers and see if there's a way that we can work together.

Look forward to hearing from you!

biography:
Running a business takes lots of time and sometimes there just isn’t enough time to look after the important area of marketing. The order book looks good at the moment, so perhaps you think you don’t need to worry about marketing at the moment. But that’s where you’re wrong. Unless you keep your eye firmly on the needs of your customers, you might not have any customers next week.

That’s why you need to draw up a marketing plan and start putting in place the strategies vital for the long-term growth of your business. But not flowery words in fancy documents, practical marketing solutions that can be quickly implemented and lead to increased turnover for your business.

But do you know exactly what your customers want? You may think you do but until you actually ask customers you are actually working in the dark. Surveys and focus groups are just some of the market research expertise that Customer Sense has.

biography:
Truth was born in 2007 with a goal to bridge the gap between mainstream research and pure consultancy. We've grown rapidly to a team of more than 50 talented professionals, all driven by a belief that truth can make a difference. The most successful strategies are those which meet and anticipate change. We believe in the power of truth as a driver of change: recognising it, understanding it, and creating it.

Truth brings together an eclectic mix of expertise in business strategy, brand development, innovation and communications. This mix means that we are not tied to any one method - we have the freedom to focus on delivering the best solution to your challenge.

We help our clients build profitable brand and business strategies, based on insight into the way people think, feel and behave - the deep and distinctive truths our clients need to know to help their brands succeed.

Our job is to find truth, distil it, and bring it to life in a way that can change things for the better. We love what we do and are hoping to put our experience to good use and help out other organisations (not for profit) take their brand and business to the next level.

biography: I am the founder of CEDAR: Community Education in Death Awareness & Resources CIC. We are a social enterprise dedicated to teaching people how to talk about death and deliver bad news. I became interested in working with communities as a result of my research in this field. Over the course of my experience as a bereavement and HIV crisis counselor, researcher and teacher in Death Studies, I heard hundreds of stories around the despair and isolation one feels after a loss. In particular, if the community in which the bereaved live ignores them these feelings of isolation are magnified and can become problematic. At CEDAR we aim to bring communities and individuals together by raising awareness, building confidence to talk about death, and helping people to prepare for death and/or help those who are bereaved.

biography:

experience:
NULLARCHITECTS-IN-RESIDENCENULL

Marketers > Architects > Artists > Related Practitioners & Interns in Residence Online with the Right to Manage -- London Borough of Ealing and Beyond

The Arts & Business Award-winning SARAG Guide TMO was founded in 1997, emerging creatively from two architects-in-residence studies (with the theme 'Seeing is Believing') led by architects John Thompson & Partners in 1997 and 2000 (www.jtp.co.uk.). SARAG now seeks to contribute radically to orienting as co-operatively managed ‘shared-homes’[3] all of Britain’s council owned residential estates, starting with those of heritage-rich London Borough of Ealing as reviewed and profiled in 2005 by the architecture & masterplanning consultancy EDAW/AECOM (www.edaw.com)[4].  

                                                      NULLTHE FATHER OF ADVERTISINGNULL                   

The RTM is in many ways akin to the ‘Aided Self-Help’ social housing component of Puerto Rico’s 1950s ‘Operation Bootstrap’:  a smartly marketed made-in-the-Caribbean socio-economic development programme in which ‘Father of Advertising’, David Ogilvy played the lead role. This assignment, in his own words, he deemed his “proudest achievement.”  So there we have it, the potential of the RTM, from the patriarch himself.[5] 

The Right To Manage makes heritage count supremely: “The further backward you look, the further forward you can see” -Winston S Churchill); “Open your eyes and look, in this great future you can’t forget the past” – Bob Marley

London’s Courtauld Institute art graduate Gillian Darley is an award-winning architectural and landscape journalist/author. Her biographies of celebrated 17th century diarist John Evelyn, the John Ruskin mentored social housing innovator, Octavia Hill[6], and legendary architect John Soane are all seminal.  

But the work for which it appears she is most admired is Villages of Vision. In this she unveils a fascinating area of national heritage — a neat profiling of hundreds of planned villages across Britain and Ireland. Included are Ealing’s Bedford Park and Brentham estates and four World Heritage Site candidates: Saltaire, Bournville, Port Sunlight (www.portsunlightvillage.com) and New Lanark (www.newlanark.org) – all characterised by at least a modicum of self-management [6].

                                                  NULLA REVOLUTIONARY INVENTIONNULL

Council housing, one of Britain’s truly revolutionary social inventions (easily ranking with the National Health Service in original intent), is in many ways a twentieth century up-scaled adaptation of Darley’s visionary world.   

But, alas, when the municipal architects created the council housing model[7] they mistakenly ignored Octavia Hill’s self-management vision and the Ruskin/Morris preventative maintenance mantra (“Put protection in place … to stave off decay by daily care”). That mistake was confronted 20 years ago - when Sir George Young, then Ealing-Acton MP and Tory Housing and Planning Minister, piloted through the British Parliament “Statutory Instrument No. 627, The Housing (Right to Manage) Regulations 1994”.

The period 1992 – 2013, saw three studies (by Price Waterhouse Coopers, Oxford Brookes University and Urban Forum/University of York) fully endorsing the RTM as the way to govern council-owned residential estates and blocks - see two examples: www.watmos.org.uk & www.leathermarketjmb.org.uk.

In 2002 the Tony Blair-led Labour Government extended the Right to Manage (RTM) regime to leasehold tenants in the private sector (www.rtmf.org). (There is as yet no academic study of how collaboration between the two RTM regimes in the public and private sectors could impact positively on the co-op movement.)

                                                       

                                                       NULLHOUSING MANAGEMENT CO-OPNULL

However, coming right up to date, during this 2014-2015 period, the 1994 RTM statute has had the benefit of three major boosts in LB Ealing: (1) residents of South Acton Estate registered a stunning 80% majority vote in favour of setting up their own housing management co-op (see below). Then, in the 2014 local election,the International Co-operative Alliance (ICA) saw its senior envoy on co-operative housing become an Ealing Ward Councillor. And now (3), the new MP for Ealing-Acton (elected in 2015) has declared co-operative housing fused with the garden city movement as high on her agenda.

All in all, taken together, this borough clearly has a claim to the RTM as a central feature of its patrimony[7].

Our Membership is Our Wealth, Strength & Power

 SARAG’s membership is open to all residents of South Acton Estate:         

  • secure tenants
  • non-secure/temporary tenants
  • assured tenants of housing associations
  • leaseholders & freeholders
  • tenants of leaseholders/freeholders
  • shared ownership tenants

      Associate membership is open to local non-estate residents who subscribe to SARAG’s aims. 

      SARAG knows that unity is strength – by joining together we have achieved!

      SARAG is strengthened by the diversity of the community it represents 

                                                          NULLENTITLED TO RESPECTNULL        

We oppose all discrimination whether on grounds of race, gender, sexual orientation, marriage/civil partnership, religion, age, disability, language;

  • all residents are equally valued & welcomed;  entitled to respect & courtesy;
  • the old and the young – from nurseries to sheltered housing & residential care;
  • from every corner of the globe – and all five continents;
  • from whatever type of tenure (tenants, leaseholders, freeholders);
  • workers, and job-seekers;
  • the able-bodied and those with disabilities of any kind;
  • whether financially self-sufficient or in receipt of benefits;
  • newcomers and old-timers;
  • single people and families;
  • we all pay for services - whether as rent, service charge or council tax;
  • we all pay, out of our own financial resources or through benefits to which we are entitled;       
  • we all suffer both collectively and individually if in recipt of poor services;
  • SARAG understands that there is much more to unite us than there is to divide us

Milestones, Collaborations, Seminal Projects 1997 – Present

The core of SARAG’s work is its 18 years of action research and learning campaigning aimed at resident governance of South Acton and other residential council blocks and estates in Ealing. The campaign is heritage-guided and is inspired by the William Morris’ clarion call ‘to stave off decay by daily care’ [8].

                                                     NULLHABITAT STEWARDSHIPNULL

The South Acton/Southfield Neighbourhood (SAN) in LB Ealing (LBE) is a mix of residential and commercial estates, including the large, 30-hectare multi landlord, heritage-rich South Acton Housing Estate, majority owned by our council and represented since 1997 by the Arts & Business award-winning SARAG.

The guiding mission of SARAG is the attainment of community governance of SAN.  Clause 3.2 of SARAG’s constitution mandates the organisation to: “promote, and become directly involved in the regeneration of the South Acton estate, in particular, and the Acton area as a whole in partnership with the London Borough of Ealing …” It is to this end that SARAG pursues the RTM option as a key investment in sustainable regeneration and self-managed habitat stewardship.

Almost everything that SARAG does is action-researched. Within the national culture, council housing estates are considered places with wrongs that need fixing ‘by the powers that be’. Challenged to embrace Dr Booker T Washington's NULLCast Down Your Bucket Where You AreNULL philosophy, and to always start not with what is wrong, but with what's right about the place where they live, South Actonians have emerged as a community of resilient, audacious, confident and exemplary doers! This is a community engaged in a prolonged, aesthetics driven rebellion against the status quo. The Chinese have a saying for what is being sought: Pendeng Huli = Equality and Mutual Benefit

                                                   NULLPARTICIPATIVE REGENERATIONNULL

Thus, in 2010 SARAG’s strictly residents-only Management Collective established the South Acton Community Builders Co-operative Ltd (SCBC) to pilot the 1994 statutory Right to Manage (www.nftmo.com & www.cch.coop) as a high value investment in sustainable habitat stewardship and heritage–led participative neighbourhood economic regeneration. The aim is to guide replication of the South Acton pilot elsewhere as a contribution to community empowerment generally and specifically to play a key role in the work of Co-operatives UK (www.uk.coop) which is geared to healing the bruises recently suffered by the British sector of the international co-operative movement.

 So, what if with the RTM, Britain’s 2.5 million council tenants could be mobilised to play a vanguard role in restoring ‘the co-op’ to its former glory? What if indeed …

SARAG at a glance - 1997 to Present 

2012 -- 2013: Business in the Community (BITC - www.bitc.org.uk) assesses SARAG as a candidate eligible for engagement with Pimp My Cause (www.pimpmycause.org) and for mentoring by Cambridge Education, a division of Mott MacDonald, the global employee-owned multidisciplinary consultancy (www.mottmac.com)

2008 - Present: A Ruskinian Walk Through Shared Heritage, a very popular feature of the Open House London annual architectural celebration.  The walk starts at the Richard Rogers designed, award-winning Chiswick Park Business Estate followed by a tour through the 19th, 20th and 21st architecture and 'green lungs' of South Acton. Everyone's walking about it! - www.open-city.org.uk

2005: SARAG wins Artists & Places PROJECT Award for Engaging Architects / Artists in the Built Environment (www.publicartonline.org.uk/pasw/project/awards/england/south_acton.php)  Scheme Manager, Alastair Snow (Snow Art: www.snowart.co.uk)  

2004: SARAG contributes to 'South Acton: The Management Of The Public Realm' by Campbell Tickell Consultancy (www.campbelltickell,com)

2003: Architects-in-Residents – SARAG’s Urban Design Study by a University of Westminster team: Architects Bill Erickson, David Seex and Bartlett schooled Professor Marion Roberts. A project grant-aided by the British government’s Neighbourhood Renewal Unit with budget administered by the Ealing Community & Voluntary Service

                                                   NULLACTION RESEARCH & LEARNINGNULL

  • A SARAG early-win: The founding of South Acton Skills and Arts Collaborative (SASAC) 
  • Action Acton: Founding Member Board of Management (www.actionacton.com)
  • Alliance with Ealing Family Housing Association on Harbour Lights/Barrie House Project – signal contribution to creation of Catalyst Communities Housing Association (www.chg.org.uk)
  • Aided the re-launch of Acton Community Forum (www.actonforum.org)
  • Membership LBE’s Borough Housing Policy Partnership
  • Action Research & Learning Sessions @ Change Base – second Monday of every month  
  • Partnering with the Workers’ Educational Association (WEA) on an annual Philosophy Course
  • Applied Gandhian method to save LBE’s total housing asset from ‘Large-Scale … Transfer’
  • Membership,South Acton Strategic Board & Ealing Local Strategic Partnership
  • Various consultative engagements with architects, James Monaghan, Peter Barber, representing the Glass House Unit; Llowarch Llowarch; and SARAG associate member Adrian Cook of Chiswick House
  • Open City: ‘A Ruskinian Walk Through Shared Heritage’ (www.opencity.com) annually
  • Road-Testing 'Community Gateway' which Ealing lost to Preston (www.cih.org/gateway)
  • With Ealing Civic Society’s support, lobbied LB Ealing for £50,000 to trigger ‘percent-for-art’
  • Author of widely consulted/quoted responses to planning applications made to LB Ealing
  • Designated Neighbourhood to Neighbourhood Learning Guide TMO (www.nftmo.com)
  • Founding of  South Acton Community Builders Co-operative Ltd (SCBC); becoming RTM Tenant Management Organisation (TMO) Contractor to Ealing Council in 2015; piloting an Each One Teach One (Neighbourhood to Neighbourhood Learning) RTM Programme

Footnotes:

 [1] The RTM statute of 1994 was designed to give a boost to the growth of Tenant Management Organisations (TMOs) However, it was not given the kind of fanfare advertising launch accorded the 1980 start-up of the Right to Buy (RTB). The National (NFTMO) has lamented that the RTM might be 'Britain's Best Kept Housing Secret'

biography:
I am the founder and director of Maverick Marketing Consultancy. Since 2008 I have helped to grow a diverse portfolio of companies across London and Hertfordshire. Essentially I work with organisations to build and implement a system for growth, enabling them to scale their businesses to 6 and 7-figure companies.

My proprietary approach is to work with owner-managers to help better position and communicate their uniqueness in the market place; establish a results-focused framework for growth, and to implement marketing concepts and tactics geared at creating awareness, building trust and winning clients.

In 2011 I released the Amazon 5-star rated book NULLMaverick Marketing: Essential Business-Building Strategies for Extraordinary Business GrowthNULL, which is essentially a compilation of the key concepts and teachings taken from my private consultations and training.

A ‘serial entrepreneur’ I was inspired to set up London Business Advice in 2012. London Business Advice is unique in that our small network of advisors, like myself, are all business owners and so have a very ‘real world’ understanding of what it takes to run a successful enterprise.

In 2014 I set up The Business Plan Writer – having noticed another ‘gap’ in the business support market. As a business enterprise adviser and trainer, and having spent almost 10 years’ reviewing and preparing business plans, I decided to start up a specialist consultancy. To date my professionally written business plans have already helped clients secure from as little as £3,000 to over £3.5 million in investment, enabling many businesses across the UK (as well as internationally) to expand and grow their operations.

Last year I was personally invited to contribute a chapter on the importance of business planning for the book 'The Crowdsourced Guide to Business' which contains over 250 pages of interviews from some of the UK’s leading business experts.

My interests lay in supporting causes at non-executive director, board or trustee level.

biography:
I am the founder and director of Maverick Marketing Consultancy. Since 2008 I have helped to grow a diverse portfolio of companies across London and Hertfordshire. Essentially I work with organisations to build and implement a system for growth, enabling them to scale their businesses to 6 and 7-figure companies.

My proprietary approach is to work with owner-managers to help better position and communicate their uniqueness in the market place; establish a results-focused framework for growth, and to implement marketing concepts and tactics geared at creating awareness, building trust and winning clients.

In 2011 I released the Amazon 5-star rated book NULLMaverick Marketing: Essential Business-Building Strategies for Extraordinary Business GrowthNULL, which is essentially a compilation of the key concepts and teachings taken from my private consultations and training.

A ‘serial entrepreneur’ I was inspired to set up London Business Advice in 2012. London Business Advice is unique in that our small network of advisors, like myself, are all business owners and so have a very ‘real world’ understanding of what it takes to run a successful enterprise.

In 2014 I set up The Business Plan Writer – having noticed another ‘gap’ in the business support market. As a business enterprise adviser and trainer, and having spent almost 10 years’ reviewing and preparing business plans, I decided to start up a specialist consultancy. To date my professionally written business plans have already helped clients secure from as little as £3,000 to over £3.5 million in investment, enabling many businesses across the UK (as well as internationally) to expand and grow their operations.

Last year I was personally invited to contribute a chapter on the importance of business planning for the book 'The Crowdsourced Guide to Business' which contains over 250 pages of interviews from some of the UK’s leading business experts.

My interests lay in supporting causes at non-executive director, board or trustee level.

biography:
I am co-founder of the FYI customer architecture model, CoFounder of MarketEd.Live, speaker and Virgin start-up mentor.

I have 20 years’ experience in marketing, throughout which time I have been fortunate enough to have worked with a wide variety of brands and businesses from premier league football clubs, a variety of FMCG brands, manufacturers, start-ups, professional services organisations and large pub companies.

I am also a business owner being director of two marketing businesses and CMO of another I understand what it is like starting and running a business and don’t just see things from a marketing angle but also a commercial one.

Marketing is changing:

During my 20 years as a marketing professional, I have seen a couple of major changes in marketing, the emergence of websites and of course the arrival of social media. Neither of those two changes is as big as the one we are in the midst of right now.  Marketing is changing, not only in its methods and tactics but also the industry itself with the massive influx of marketing technology arriving rapidly. What does this mean for you the business owner? I hear you say. It means simplification, personalisation, personification and automation are 4 things you need to get control of.

I champion marketing which focuses on my main value of: “People buy people” and help businesses and brands become customer centric not only in the marketing department but throughout the organisation.
